        <p>Papillotubular adenoma of the ampullary region in a rare tumor which has the potential for malignant
transformation. Although reported more frequently nowadays, ampullary tumors are difficult to diagnose
before operation unless they cause obstructive jaundice. Occasionally they are detected by
ultrasonography, computed tomography or ERCP in patients who complain of nonspecific upper
abdominal discomfort.</p>
        <p>We report a case of a periampullary papilotubular adenoma causing generalized pruritus and weight
loss but no jaundice. The tumor was extirpated by pancreaticoduodenectomy, and the patient has
remained healthy for over five years.</p>
